Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment,The original source of data can be found on kaggle.

A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row such as :.

  • ‘ScheduledDay’ tells us on what day the patient set up their appointment.
  • ‘Neighborhood’ indicates the location of the hospital.
  • ‘Scholarship’ indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Família.
  • ‘SMS_received’ If patient receive a SMS or not .
  • ‘no_show’ It says ‘No’ if the patient showed up to their appointment, and ‘Yes’ if they did not show up.

Question for Analysis¶

  1. what is the percentage of people who do show vs people who do not show ?
  2. What factors are important for us to know in order to predict if a patient will show up for their scheduled appointment?

# Pie Chart
def pac_man(Chart_values, colour, legend, title, angle ):
    """
    Creates a pie chart

    Args:
        Chart_values: the values inside the pie chart
        colour: colours of the different values
        legend: legend of the chart
        title: the title for the chart
        angle: the start-angle

    Returns:
        The chart graph
    """
    plt.pie(Chart_values, explode=(0, 0.1), colors =colour ,shadow=True, autopct='%.1f%%', startangle=angle)
    plt.axis('scaled')
    plt.legend(legend)
    plt.title(title)
    return plt.show()


# Bar chart 1
def kitkat_bar(x_axis_values , y_axis_values, color, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    """
    Creates a Bar chart with single value on x axis

    Args:
        x_axis_values : represent the values on x axis
        y_axis_values:  represent the values on y axis
        color: colours of the different values
        title: the title for the chart
        xlabel: name of the x axis
        ylabel: name of the y axis

    Returns:
        The chart graph
    """
    plt.figure(figsize=(4, 4))
    plt.title(title, fontsize=15)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.bar(x_axis_values, y_axis_values, color=color, width=0.3, )
    return plt.show()


# Bar chart 2
def twix_bar(Chart_values, color, xticklabels, xlabel, ylabel, legend, title):
    """
    Creates a Bar chart with multi value on x axis

    Args:
        Chart_values: The values inside the bar chart
        color: colours of the different values
        xticklabels: The names of the different values of the x axis
        xlabel: represent the values on x axis
        ylabel: represent the values on y axis
        legend: legend of the chart
        title: the title for the chart

    Returns:
        The chart graph
    """
    ax = Chart_values.plot.bar(figsize=(5, 5), color=color)
    ax.set_xticklabels(xticklabels, fontsize=15, rotation=0)
    ax.set_ylabel(ylabel)
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel)
    ax.legend(legend)
    ax.set_title(title)
    return plt.show()


# Line chart
def line(Chart_values, color, xlabel, ylabel, legend, title):
    """
    Creats a line chart

    Args:
        Chart_values: The values inside the line chart
        color: colours of the different values
        xlabel: represent the values on x axis
        ylabel: represent the values on y axis
        legend: legend of the chart
        title: the title for the chart

    Returns:
        The chart graph
    """
    ax = Chart_values.plot(figsize=(5, 5), color=color)
    ax.legend(legend)
    ax.set_title(title)
    ax.set_ylabel(ylabel)
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel)
    return plt.show()

Conclusions¶

  • The percentage of people who did show up was 79.8% and who didn't was 20.2%.
  • The number of females was 71,839 and males was 38,687 through the observation periode
  • The proportion of males was a little bit higher than the female's proportion
  • The higher the age segment goes, the higher Patients tend to show up and less to no show, but still, the kid's age segment has a higher number on show up than the young's segment according to the second bar chart, the higher the age segment goes, the higher patients tend to show up and less to no show, but still, the kid's age segment has a higher number on show up than the young's segment
  • It seems like 9.8% have scholarship and 90.2% of patients have no No-Scholarship
  • It seems like patients who have no scholarship tend to have a higher rate on show up than patients who have a scholarship
  • 75,044 patients didn't receive an SMS but on the other hand 35,482 patients received SMS
  • Patients proportions who didn't receive SMS have a higher show-up rate.
  • Waiting time doesn't tend to have that much effect on the show-up rate

Limitations¶

  • The dataset's observation period was too short .
  • Data set should have more data such as illness.
  • Location of the clinic vs the neighborhood location.
  • Advanced time serises analyis can be done on waiting time .
  • Advanced statistical analysis can be on the data set, not only on factories that affect show and no show rate but on other things such as waiting time vs SMS received and more data should be given on when SMS is being sent and what the conditions to sent a SMS.

we going to split our data to 2 main parts X and y :

in simple speaking we X is the input and y will be the result we want.
